         <h1>James Laughlin, Publisher With Bold Taste, Dies at 83 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>James Laughlin , the fiercely independent publisher , editor and poet , who , as the founder and longtime head of New Directions , published many of the most consequential and revolutionary writers of his time , died Wednesday on the way to Sharon Hospital from his home in Norfolk , Conn . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 83 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was complications following a stroke , said Griselda Ohannessian , the managing director of New Directions . <br><blue>4</blue>A man who combined bold taste with a gentle demeanor , Mr. Laughlin made a major contribution to literature as well as to the field of publishing . <br><blue>5</blue>The list of his writers is staggering in its length and artistic complexity . <br><blue>6</blue>He was Vladimir Nabokov 's first American publisher and also printed the work of Tennessee Williams , William Carlos Williams , Ezra Pound , Henry Miller , Djuna Barnes , Dylan Thomas , Delmore Schwartz and John Hawkes , among many others . <br><blue>7</blue>There are large publishing houses and small presses -- and then there is New Directions , a one-man operation that grew to become one of the most influential book companies in the United States . '' <br><blue>8</blue>He was the greatest publisher America ever had , '' Brendan Gill , an author and critic , said yesterday . '' <br><blue>9</blue>Look at his backlist : there 's nothing comparable . '' <br><blue>10</blue>As the poet Donald Hall said in an article in The New York Times in 1981 , two things were paramount on Mr. Laughlin 's list : '' the assumption of quality and the assumption that these books would not sell in the marketplace . '' <br><blue>11</blue>He added that Mr. Laughlin started New Directions '' in the service of verbal revolution , '' but he also reprinted Henry James , E. M. Forster , Ronald Firbank and Evelyn Waugh '' when other publishers would not . '' <br><blue>12</blue>Mr. Laughlin was , Mr. Hall said , a publisher '' of the middle way , '' someone '' who by low overhead , by infusions of capital from the responsible rich , by wit , or most likely by all three -- can choose with taste , publish with economy and keep a good book in print . '' <br><blue>13</blue>Mr. Laughlin published '' The Crack Up '' by F. Scott Fitzgerald ; Beat poets including Lawrence Ferlinghetti and Gregory Corso ; as well as authors in translation ( Pablo Neruda , Garcia Lorca , Boris Pasternak , Jorge Luis Borges , Yukio Mishima ) , and on and on . <br><blue>14</blue>He was indefatigable in his search for the new and adventurous . <br><blue>15</blue>In a field often known for its timidity and for its concern for profits above all , Mr. Laughlin was a maverick . <br><blue>16</blue>As he once said , '' I do n't have any business acumen . <br><blue>17</blue>I 'm not good at deals and ca n't cope with agents . '' <br><blue>18</blue>What he could cope with were the personalities of some of the most difficult and temperamental authors . <br><blue>19</blue>With a characteristic boldness , he would take chances on anyone he considered an original . <br><blue>20</blue>At the recommendation of Pound , he took on William Carlos Williams and Henry Miller . <br><hr><br><blue>1(5)</blue>: <m_str>A man who combined bold taste with a gentle demeanor , Mr. Laughlin</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (5_4) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (9_3) 	<br><blue>2(1)</blue>: <m_str>Pound</m_str> (20_5) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>William Carlos Williams</m_str> (20_10) 	<m_str>William Carlos Williams</m_str> (6_18) 	<br><blue>4(1)</blue>: <m_str>Vladimir Nabokov 's</m_str> (6_3) 	<br><blue>5(3)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (1_47) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_35) 	<br><blue>6(1)</blue>: <m_str>Djuna Barnes</m_str> (6_28) 	<br><blue>7(4)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Hall</m_str> (12_5) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (11_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (11_19) 	<m_str>Donald Hall</m_str> (10_4) 	<br><blue>8(2)</blue>: <m_str>The list of his writers</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>its</m_str> (5_9) 	<br><blue>9(2)</blue>: <m_str>New Directions</m_str> (3_17) 	<m_str>New Directions</m_str> (1_22) 	<br><blue>10(1)</blue>: <m_str>Norfolk , Conn.</m_str> (1_50) 	<br><blue>11(2)</blue>: <m_str>Henry Miller</m_str> (6_25) 	<m_str>Henry Miller</m_str> (20_14) 	<br><blue>12(15)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Laughlin</m_str> (15_18) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_2) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (16_7) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (18_2) 	<m_str>Mr. Laughlin</m_str> (11_4) 	<m_str>Mr. Laughlin 's</m_str> (10_23) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_6) 	<m_str>Mr. Laughlin</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_12) 	<m_str>Mr. Laughlin</m_str> (4_12) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (20_7) 	<m_str>Mr. Laughlin</m_str> (13_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_5) 	<br><blue>13(2)</blue>: <m_str>its</m_str> (15_7) 	<m_str>its</m_str> (15_11) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
